    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="1049"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1049">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Department of the Army Files: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1049<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_CWL1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clayton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief of the Mission for Economic Affairs
                        in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BTCJ1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Blaisdell</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d1049fn1">Sent over the signature of <persName
                            corresp="#p_BJF1">Byrnes</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Babelsberg</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-29">July 29,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Victory1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Victory</hi>
                    </gloss> 416. For <persName corresp="#p_BTCJ1">Blaisdell</persName> from
                        <persName corresp="#p_CWL1">Clayton</persName>.</p>
                <p>I am informed that <gloss target="#t_War1">War</gloss> Cabinet adopted
                    substantially the recommendations outlined in your 7382, July 21 to
                        Washington.<note n="2" xml:id="d1049fn2">
                        <ref target="#d1042">Document No. 1042</ref>.</note> Believe we should
                    strongly urge the British to revise this decision and to maintain export to
                    Europe of usable grades of <gloss target="#t_UK1">U. K.</gloss> coal at former
                    rates. Our allocation of six million tons for Europe will in any event arouse
                    some criticism, owing to prospective shortage for domestic heating and to our
                    strained shipping and inland transport position. If at same time exports from
                        <gloss target="#t_UK1">U. K.</gloss> are discontinued criticism will be
                    accentuated. Despite tightness of British coal position, it should be possible
                    to maintain quarter of a million tons monthly for European relief instead of
                    transferring whole supply burden to U. S.</p>
            </div>
